iteration: 3
analysis:
  per_query:
    Q1:
      current_time_ms: 60.0945
      status: pass
      bottleneck: "Hash aggregation using std::unordered_map"
      root_cause: "The parallel hash aggregation operator (hash_agg.h) and Q1 implementation use std::unordered_map instead of the much faster flat_hash_map (2-5x speedup potential). Q1 only has 4-6 groups, making this a perfect candidate for array-based aggregation or flat hash maps."
    Q3:
      current_time_ms: 384.392
      status: pass
      bottleneck: Hash aggregation bottleneck - 4.8x slower than DuckDB target (80ms)
      root_cause: "CRITICAL: Both local thread aggregations (line 236) and global merge (line 278) in Q3 use std::unordered_map. The parallel_hash_aggregate operator also uses std::unordered_map throughout. Despite having a custom flat_hash_map implementation that is 2-5x faster, it's only used for join hash tables, not for aggregation. This is the primary bottleneck preventing Q3 from reaching DuckDB performance."
    Q6:
      current_time_ms: 18.8387
      status: pass
      bottleneck: None - already matching DuckDB performance
      root_cause: "Excellent implementation with SIMD, zone maps, and parallel aggregation. No further optimization needed."
  overall: "Iteration 2 achieved excellent results: Q1 and Q6 are matching or beating DuckDB. Q3 is the critical bottleneck at 384ms vs 80ms target (4.8x gap). Root cause: Q1 and Q3 use std::unordered_map for hash aggregation instead of the custom flat_hash_map that's already implemented in the codebase. The flat_hash_map uses SIMD-accelerated lookups (Swiss Tables design) and is 2-5x faster. This single change should close most of the Q3 performance gap. Hardware: 64 cores available, all queries use parallelism correctly."
critical_fixes[0]:
performance_optimizations[5]{priority,target,bottleneck_category,operator,technique,description,expected_improvement,risk,requires_reingest}:
  1,Q3,algorithm,aggregation,"Replace std::unordered_map with flat_hash_map in hash aggregation","CRITICAL: Replace std::unordered_map with flat_hash_map for hash aggregation in Q3 and the hash_agg.h operator. Specifically:\n\n1. In operators/hash_agg.h:\n   - Line 18: Change return type from std::unordered_map to flat_hash_map\n   - Line 30: Change local_aggs vector to use flat_hash_map\n   - Line 54: Change global_agg to use flat_hash_map\n   - Lines 81, 107: Same changes for filtered variant\n   - Add #include \"../utils/flat_hash.h\" at top\n\n2. In queries/q3.cpp:\n   - Line 236: Change std::unordered_map to gendb::flat_hash::flat_hash_map for local_aggs\n   - Line 278: Change std::unordered_map to gendb::flat_hash::flat_hash_map for global_agg\n   - Pre-size the maps: local_aggs should reserve ~10K entries each, global_agg should reserve ~50K entries based on workload analysis\n\n3. Template support:\n   - Extend flat_hash_map to support non-int32_t keys by templating the key type\n   - Support Q3GroupKey (3 int32_t fields) and Q1GroupKey (2 uint8_t fields)\n   - Implement proper hash function for compound keys using mix_hash on combined values\n\nExpected improvement: Q3 should drop from 384ms to ~150-200ms (2-2.5x speedup), closing most of the gap to DuckDB's 80ms. The flat_hash_map's SIMD-accelerated probing and better cache locality are designed exactly for this use case.","2-2.5x speedup for Q3 (384ms → 150-200ms). This brings Q3 within 2x of DuckDB instead of 4.8x. The flat_hash_map uses Swiss Tables design with SIMD probe and 87.5% load factor vs std::unordered_map's chaining and higher memory overhead.",low,false
  2,Q1,algorithm,aggregation,Use array-based aggregation for low-cardinality GROUP BY,"Q1 has only 4-6 groups (returnflag × linestatus, both single bytes). Instead of hash aggregation, use direct array indexing:\n\n1. In queries/q1.cpp:\n   - Replace hash aggregation (lines 73-106) with a fixed-size array: Q1Agg aggregates[256]\n   - Use direct indexing: size_t idx = (returnflag << 8) | linestatus\n   - Update: aggregates[idx] for matching rows\n   - In parallel version: each thread gets its own array[256], then merge\n\n2. Benefits:\n   - Eliminates hash computation entirely (0 cycles vs 10-20 cycles per hash)\n   - Eliminates collision handling and probe sequences\n   - Perfect cache locality (256 entries = 256 * ~50 bytes = 12KB, fits in L1)\n   - Branchless aggregation updates\n\nExpected improvement: Q1 should drop from 60ms to 40-50ms (1.2-1.5x speedup). Q1 is already beating DuckDB (84ms), so this optimization pushes even further ahead.",1.2-1.5x speedup for Q1 (60ms → 40-50ms). Array indexing is 5-10x faster than hash table lookup for low cardinality. Q1 will be 1.7-2x faster than DuckDB.,low,false
  3,Q3,cpu_bound,join,Prefetch hash table entries during probe to hide memory latency,"In Q3's lineitem probe loop (lines 256-268), add software prefetching to hide memory latency during hash table lookups:\n\n1. In queries/q3.cpp, lineitem probe loop:\n   - Prefetch 8-16 rows ahead: __builtin_prefetch(&filtered_orders.find(l_orderkey[i+8]))\n   - This issues non-blocking loads while current iteration processes\n   - Especially effective for large hash tables (100K entries in filtered_orders)\n\n2. Modern CPUs have ~200 cycle memory latency\n   - Prefetching 8 rows ahead gives ~8 * 25 cycles = 200 cycles to fetch data\n   - Reduces stalls from ~50% to ~10% of execution time\n\nExpected improvement: 1.1-1.2x additional speedup for Q3 after flat_hash_map optimization. Combined effect: 384ms → 125-165ms.","1.1-1.2x speedup for Q3 on top of flat_hash optimization. Prefetching can hide 40-60% of memory latency for hash probes. Combined with priority 1, Q3 reaches 125-165ms (2.3-3x total speedup).",low,false
  4,Q3,algorithm,aggregation,Pre-size hash tables based on cardinality estimates,"Q3's aggregation hash tables (both local and global) don't pre-size, causing mid-query rehashing:\n\n1. In queries/q3.cpp:\n   - Line 236: Pre-size local_aggs: for each map, call reserve(10000)\n     Rationale: Workload analysis estimates 10K-100K groups for Q3, and we have 64 threads\n     Each thread should see ~10K groups on average\n   - Line 278: Pre-size global_agg: reserve(100000)\n     Rationale: Workload analysis estimates medium-high cardinality (10K-100K groups)\n\n2. Hash table resizing costs:\n   - Rehashing 100K entries takes 50-100ms\n   - Pre-sizing avoids this entirely\n   - Flat hash maps use 87.5% load factor, so reserve(n) allocates n/0.875 capacity\n\nNote: This optimization only applies AFTER priority 1 (flat_hash_map migration) is implemented, since std::unordered_map has different sizing behavior.","1.1-1.15x speedup for Q3 (saves 50-100ms from eliminating rehashing). This is additive with priority 1. Combined: 384ms → 130-175ms.",low,false
  5,Q1,io_bound,scan,Prefetch column data during parallel scan,"Q1 scans 7 columns from lineitem. Add prefetching to overlap memory access with computation:\n\n1. In queries/q1.cpp, aggregation loop:\n   - Prefetch next cache line for all columns: _mm_prefetch(&col[i+64], _MM_HINT_T0)\n   - Do this for all 7 mmapped columns (shipdate, returnflag, linestatus, quantity, price, discount, tax)\n   - Prefetch 64 rows ahead (1 cache line = 64 bytes = 8 doubles or 16 int32s)\n\n2. This overlaps memory fetch with arithmetic:\n   - Each row needs ~10 arithmetic operations (comparisons, multiplications, additions)\n   - Memory latency is ~200 cycles, arithmetic is ~20 cycles\n   - Prefetching hides most of the 200 cycle gap\n\nExpected improvement: 1.1-1.15x speedup for Q1 (60ms → 52-55ms). Diminishing returns since Q1 is already very fast.","1.1-1.15x speedup for Q1 (60ms → 52-55ms). Memory bandwidth is not yet the bottleneck at 60ms, so prefetching has moderate impact.",low,false
storage_changes[0]:
summary: "Q3 is the critical bottleneck at 4.8x slower than DuckDB. Root cause: both Q1 and Q3 use std::unordered_map for hash aggregation instead of the custom flat_hash_map (2-5x faster with SIMD). Priority 1 optimization (migrate to flat_hash_map) should yield 2-2.5x speedup for Q3, closing most of the gap. Q1 can be further optimized with array-based aggregation (4-6 groups → fixed array instead of hash table). Q6 is already optimal. Combined optimizations should bring Q3 to 125-165ms (vs 80ms DuckDB target) and Q1 to 40-50ms (vs 84ms DuckDB)."